entry.title: Coastal Flood Warning issued March 10 at 3:50AM EDT until March 10 at 7:00AM EDT by NWS Wakefield VA
entry.summary:
* WHAT...Up the Rappahannock River to Tappahannock, 1 to 2 feet of inundation above ground level is expected a few hours on either side of high tide tonight. Elsewhere closer to the Chesapeake Bay, up to one foot of inundation above ground level in low- lying areas near shorelines and tidal waterways.
* WHERE...Richmond, Lancaster, Middlesex, Mathews and Eastern Essex Counties.
* WHEN...Until 7 AM EDT this morning.
* IMPACTS...Up the Rappahannock River to Tappahannock, Widespread flooding of vulnerable areas will result in an elevated threat of property damage to homes and businesses near the waterfront and shoreline. Water will be 1 to 2 feet above ground level in some areas resulting in a sufficient depth to close numerous roads and threaten homes and businesses. Flooding will extend inland from the waterfront along tidal rivers and bays resulting in some road closures and flooding of vehicles. Elsewhere, shallow flooding is expected in the most vulnerable locations near the waterfront and shoreline resulting in a low threat of property damage. entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued March 9 at 9:13PM AKST by NWS Juneau AK
entry.summary:
Long range computer models are coming into agreement about moderate to heavy rain and warming temperatures returning to SE AK.
It's looking like a band of moisture over the north Pacific will stream northeast and into the panhandle starting near the middle of next week, bringing moderate to heavy precip to the area. Then over the latter part of the week, this band of moisture looks to move north through the panhandle, bringing another round of increased rain rates. Rainfall totals are looking moderate to heavy with 24 hour totals mostly in the 1 to 2 inch range, though locally heavier amounts are possible.
In addition to the heavy precip, another concern is a nose of warmer air that is projected to move into the panhandle. This nose of warmer air could push snow levels to over 4000 feet across the southern panhandle and 2000 to 3500 feet over the northern panhandle by next weekend.
Surface temperatures will respond as well. Next Saturday, computer models are giving the entire panhandle a 70 to 100% chance of seeing max temps greater than 40 degrees. For max temps greater than 45 degrees, areas along and south of Frederick Sound have a 60 to 100% chance while areas to the north of Frederick Sound have a 10 to 40% chance of seeing max temps greater than 45 degrees.
What's more impressive is areas to the south of Frederick Sound have a 30 to 50% chance of seeing temps above 50 degrees next Saturday - with parts of southern Prince of Wales Island and Metlakatla having a 70 to 75% chance of seeing temps above 50. Areas north of Frederick Sound have a less than 10% chance of seeing temps above 50 degrees.
Because of all this potential warmer air and heavy rain, another factor to keep an eye on is increased stream flow that could cause flooding along streams and rivers. We will continue to maintain a watch over this potential hazardous situation.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued March 9 at 2:47PM AKST by NWS Juneau AK
entry.summary:
A developing moisture band over the North Pacific will stream northeast and into the panhandle starting mid next week, then over the later part of the week it move north through the panhandle with another round of increased rain rates and warming temperatures. Rainfall totals are looking moderate to heavy with 24 hour totals in the 1 to 2 inch range. The main item to watch is a nose of warmer air will move into the panhandle that will push freezing levels over 4000 feet across the southern panhandle and 1000 to 2000 over the north central panhandle.
The item to keep an eye on is additional snow melt from warming along with the rainfall of the heavier rainfall that stream flow will have higher water levels. We will continue to maintain a watch over this potential hazardous situation.

entry.title: Fire Weather Watch issued March 9 at 5:59AM MST until March 11 at 6:00PM MST by NWS Albuquerque NM
entry.summary:
...FIRE WEATHER WATCH MONDAY AFTERNOON UNTIL EARLY EVENING FOR THE NORTHEAST PLAINS DUE TO STRONG WINDS AND LOW HUMIDITIES...
.An upper level trough crossing Colorado, and a surface trough in the lee of the southern Rockies, will cause southwest winds to gust up to 40 mph across much of northeast New Mexico on Monday afternoon until sunset. Humidities will also plummet below 15 percent while temperatures climb up to 12 degrees above 1991 to 2020 averages.
The National Weather Service in Albuquerque has issued a Fire Weather Watch...which is in effect from Monday afternoon through Monday evening.
* AREA AND TIMING...Northeast plains from 1 PM until 7 PM MDT on Monday. The most critical conditions are expected during mid to late afternoon.
* 20 FOOT WINDS...Southwest from 15 to 30 mph with gusts up to 40 mph.
* RELATIVE HUMIDITY...Dropping between 9 and 15 percent.
* IMPACTS...Please advise the appropriate officials or fire crews in the field of this Fire Weather Watch.

cap:parameter.value: FIRE WEATHER WATCH IN EFFECT FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON THROUGH MONDAY EVENING
